ST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":23,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Thweng was born in 1292, in Sefton, Lancashire, England. She married Jordan Elall Forester of Wyresdale before 1310, in Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1317, in Lancashire, England, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1292–1317":"1292–1317","1285–1317":"1285–1317","1314–1372":"1314–1372","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","before 1310":"enne 1310","about 1314":"umbes 1314","1285":"1285","1372":"1372","1292":"1292","1317":"1317","Over Wyresdale, Lancashire, England":"Over Wyresdale, Lancashire, England","Wyresdale, Lancashire, England":"Over Wyresdale, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1292–1317":"1292–131